{"title_page": "Mechi Multiple Campus", "text_new": "{{Coord|26.560768|N|88.086594|E|type:edu|display=title}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}  \n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}} \n{{Infobox university\n| name = Mechi Multiple Campus\n| native_name = \u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940 \u092c\u0939\u0941\u092e\u0941\u0916\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938\n| native_name_lang = ne\n| image_name = Mechi Multiple Campus 1.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Western entrance to the campus\n| established = 1964 (2021 BS)\n| type = [[Public]]\n| affiliation = [[Tribhuvan University]]\n| address = [[Bhadrapur, Mechi|Bhadrapur]]-8, [[Jhapa]]\n| city = \n| country = [[Nepal]]\n| sports_nickname = MMC\n| principal = Kamal Prasad Guragain\n| academic_staff = 126\n| administrative_staff = 54\n| students = 1,800\n| campus = [[Rural area]], 27 acres\n| language = [[Nepali language|Nepali]], [[English language|English]]\n| website = http://mechicampus.edu.np\n}}\n\n'''Mechi Multiple Campus''' ({{lang-ne|[[:ne:\u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940 \u092c\u0939\u0941\u092e\u0941\u0916\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938|\u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940 \u092c\u0939\u0941\u092e\u0941\u0916\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938]]}}) is a constituent campus of [[Tribhuvan University]] in [[Bhadrapur, Mechi|Bhadrapur]] municipality of [[Jhapa]] district.<ref name=\"mechi\">{{cite web|title=Homepage of Mechi Multiple Campus|url=http://www.mechicampus.edu.np/|publisher=Mechi Multiple Campus|accessdate=4 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"TU\">{{cite web|title=List of Constituent Campuses|url=http://tribhuvan-university.edu.np/academics/campuses/|website=|publisher=Tribhuvan University|accessdate=26 June 2016}}</ref> Founded in 1964, it is the only constituent campus of Tribhuvan University in the district.<ref name=\"MMC\">{{cite web|last1=Basistha|first1=Chudamani|title=\u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940 \u092c\u0939\u0941\u092e\u0941\u0916\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938 \u0939\u093f\u091c\u094b, \u0906\u091c \u0930 \u092d\u094b\u0932\u093f|url=http://www.sajhamanch.com/profile/3007.html|website=sajhamanch.com|date=1 September 2014|accessdate=26 June 2016}}</ref> As of August 2017, 126 academic and 54 administrative staffs were employed at the college.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.blastkhabar.com/news/2018/08/11/90387.html|title=\u092a\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0935\u093f\u0927\u093f\u0915 \u0936\u093f\u0915\u094d\u0937\u093e\u0932\u0947 \u092b\u0947\u0930\u093f\u090f\u0915\u094b \u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940 \u092c\u0939\u0941\u092e\u0941\u0916\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938|last=|first=|date=|website=Blast Khabar|language=ne-NP|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-09|quote=\u0967 \u0938\u092f \u0968\u096c \u091c\u0928\u093e \u0936\u093f\u0915\u094d\u0937\u0915 \u0930 \u096b\u096a \u091c\u0928\u093e \u0915\u0930\u094d\u092e\u091a\u093e\u0930\u0940 \u0915\u093e\u0930\u094d\u092f\u0930\u0924 \u0930\u0939\u0947\u0915\u094b \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0936\u093e\u0938\u0928 \u0936\u093e\u0916\u093e\u0932\u0947 \u091c\u0928\u093e\u090f\u0915\u094b \u091b \u0964}}</ref> Since June 2016, the college administration has been headed by Kamal Prasad Guragain, who is often referred to as \"Campus Chief.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khabarmanch.com/campus-chief/|title=\u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940 \u092c\u0939\u0941\u092e\u0941\u0916\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938\u0915\u094b \u092a\u094d\u0930\u092e\u0941\u0916\u092e\u093e \u0915\u092e\u0932 \u0917\u0941\u0930\u093e\u0917\u093e\u0908\u0901|date=18 June 2016|website=khabarmanch.com|language=Nepali|accessdate=11 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nTo begin with, the college offered an [[Intermediate of Arts]] (IA) program in [[humanities]], which was soon followed by undergraduate programs. At present, the college runs undergraduate and postgraduate programs. The intermediate programs were fully scrapped in 2010, following Tribhuvan University's decision to phase out Proficiency Certificate Level (PCL) programs from its colleges. This termination of PCL programs brought about a sharp decline in the number of students at the college.<ref name = \"MMC\"/> In its heyday, the college had about 5,000 students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.blastkhabar.com/news/2018/08/11/90387.html|title=\u092a\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0935\u093f\u0927\u093f\u0915 \u0936\u093f\u0915\u094d\u0937\u093e\u0932\u0947 \u092b\u0947\u0930\u093f\u090f\u0915\u094b \u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940 \u092c\u0939\u0941\u092e\u0941\u0916\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938|last=|first=|date=|website=Blast Khabar|language=ne-NP|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-09|quote=\u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938\u092e\u093e \u096b \u0939\u091c\u093e\u0930 \u0935\u093f\u0926\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0930\u094d\u0925\u0940 \u0905\u0927\u094d\u092f\u092f\u0928\u0915\u093e \u0932\u093e\u0917\u093f \u0906\u0907\u0930\u0939\u0947\u0915\u094b \u0905\u0935\u0938\u094d\u0925\u093e\u092e\u093e \u0935\u093f\u0936\u094d\u0935\u0935\u093f\u0926\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0932\u092f\u0932\u0947 \u0928\u093f\u092f\u092e \u092e\u093f\u091a\u0947\u0930 \u090f\u0915 \u0915\u093f\u0932\u094b\u092e\u093f\u091f\u0930\u0915\u094b \u0926\u0942\u0930\u0940\u092e\u093e \u0938\u094d\u0928\u093e\u0924\u0915 \u0924\u0939 \u0905\u0927\u094d\u092f\u092f\u0928\u0915\u094b \u0932\u093e\u0917\u093f \u0905\u0928\u0941\u092e\u0924\u093f \u0926\u093f\u090f\u0915\u093e \u0915\u093e\u0930\u0923 \u0935\u093f\u0926\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0930\u094d\u0925\u0940 \u0938\u0919\u094d\u0916\u094d\u092f\u093e \u0918\u091f\u0947\u0915\u094b \u0909\u0928\u0932\u0947 \u092c\u0924\u093e\u090f \u0964}}</ref> Today the number is around 1,800.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jhapaonline.com/?p=24349|title=\u0917\u0941\u0932\u094d\u091c\u093e\u0930\u200c \u092e\u0947\u200c\u091a\u0940 \u092c\u0939\u0941\u092e\u0941\u0916\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938|last=|first=|date=2019-08-28|website=Jhapa Online|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-09|quote=\u0915\u0941\u0928\u0948\u200c \u092c\u0947\u200c\u0932\u093e \u0932\u0917\u092d\u0917 \u096d \u0938\u092f \u0935\u093f\u0926\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0930\u094d\u0925\u0940 \u092e\u093e\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u0905\u0927\u094d\u092f\u092f\u0928 \u0917\u0928\u0947\u0930\u094d\u200c \u092f\u094b\u200c \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938\u092e\u093e \u0939\u093e\u0932 \u0967,\u096e\u0966\u0966 \u0935\u093f\u0926\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0930\u094d\u0925\u0940 \u0935\u093f\u092d\u093f\u0928\u094d\u0928 \u0938\u0902\u0915\u093e\u092f\u0917\u0924 \u0935\u093f\u0937\u092f\u092e\u093e \u0905\u0927\u094d\u092f\u092f\u0928\u0930\u200c\u0924\u094d \u091b\u0928\u094d\u202f\u0964}}</ref> The college received the Quality Assurance and Accreditation (QAA) certification from the University Grants Commission (UGC) on March 6, 2019.\n\n==History==\n\nWith inauguration by Brigadier General Bhupalman Singh Karki, Mechi Multiple Campus was established on 12 Ashwin 2021 [[Vikram Samvat|BS]] (27 September 1964 CE). With no private building for the next five years, classes in those early years of inception were imparted only in the evening, in the premises of Bhadrapur Red Cross and Bhadrapur High School. The construction of college's physical infrastructure began to gather pace from 2024{{nbsp}}[[Vikram Samvat|BS]] ({{circa}}{{nbsp}}1967{{nbsp}}CE),{{efn|Because [[Vikram Samvat]] leads the [[Gregorian calendar]] by 56.7 years, the CE year can be best approximated by subtracting 56.7 from the BS year and rounding it down to the nearest integral value.}} and it took three years until completion. The college was relocated to its present place in 2027{{nbsp}}[[Vikram Samvat|BS]] ({{circa}}{{nbsp}}1970{{nbsp}}CE).<ref name = \"MMC\"/>\n\nThe college celebrated its golden jubilee in the year 2071{{nbsp}}[[Vikram Samvat|BS]].<ref name=\"mechi\"/> The golden jubilee was commemorated with programmes and extra-curricular activities all year round, including a major three-day cultural event in Ashwin.<ref name=\"majheri\">{{cite web|title=\u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938 \u092d\u0926\u094d\u0930\u092a\u0941\u0930\u0915\u093e\u0947 \u0938\u0942\u091a\u0928\u093e|url=http://www.majheri.com/node/15043|website=majheri.com|accessdate=13 August 2016|language=Nepali|date=22 July 2014}}</ref> Inaugurated by the then-President [[Ram Baran Yadav]], who was the chief guest, the cultural event saw attendance from a host of alumni, donors, politicians, and national dignitaries{{Snd}}including the then-Governor of [[Nepal Rastra Bank]] Yuba Raj Khatiwada, the [[Nepali Congress]] leader Krishna Prasad Sitaula, and [[Communist Party of Nepal (Unified Marxist\u2013Leninist)|CPN\u2013UML]]'s Agni Kharel.<ref name=\"nepaljapan\">{{cite web|title=\u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940 \u092c\u0939\u0941\u092e\u0941\u0916\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938\u0915\u094b \u0938\u094d\u0935\u0930\u094d\u0923 \u092e\u0939\u094b\u0924\u094d\u0938\u0935|url=http://www.nepaljapan.com/%E0%A4%AE%E0%A5%87%E0%A4%9A%E0%A5%80-%E0%A4%AC%E0%A4%B9%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%AE%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%96%E0%A5%80-%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%AF%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%AE%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%AA%E0%A4%B8%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%8B/|website=nepaljapan.com|accessdate=13 August 2016|language=Nepali|date=19 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"nagarikfm\">{{cite web|title=\u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940 \u092c\u0939\u0941\u092e\u0941\u0916\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938\u0915\u094b \u0938\u094d\u0935\u0930\u094d\u0923\u092e\u0939\u094b\u0924\u094d\u0935\u0938 \u0938\u092e\u093e\u0930\u094b\u0939 \u092d\u0935\u094d\u092f\u0924\u093e\u0915\u093e \u0938\u093e\u0925 \u0938\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0928\u094d\u0928|url=http://www.nagarikfm.com.np/news/%E0%A4%AE%E0%A5%87%E0%A4%9A%E0%A5%80-%E0%A4%AC%E0%A4%B9%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%AE%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%96%E0%A5%80-%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%AF%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%AE%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%AA%E0%A4%B8%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%8B/|website=nagarikfm.com.np|accessdate=13 August 2016|language=Nepali|date=20 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160814104218/http://www.nagarikfm.com.np/news/%E0%A4%AE%E0%A5%87%E0%A4%9A%E0%A5%80-%E0%A4%AC%E0%A4%B9%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%AE%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%96%E0%A5%80-%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%AF%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%AE%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%AA%E0%A4%B8%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%8B/|archive-date=14 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\n\nThe campus, which spreads over an area of 16 [[bigha]]s ({{circa}} 27 acres),{{efn|The [[bigha]] is a local unit of land measurement, standardized to 72,000 square feet.|name=|group=}} is in a rural environment, about 1&nbsp;km northeast of [[Bhadrapur Airport]]. The area has a mediocre access to road transportation. The campus yard constitutes a small canteen, a cricket and a football ground, a semi-constructed basketball court, a tea garden, a soil test lab, an administrative building, a FSU building, and two other major buildings{{Spaced en dash}}one for the science faculty and the other for the rest. A second building in the science yard is also under construction.<ref name = \"mechi\"/>\n\n==Academics==\n[[File:Mechi Multiple Campus.jpg|thumb|300 px|Science block of Mechi Multiple Campus (2015)]]\nThe college offers the following undergraduate and postgraduate programs:<ref name = \"MMC\"/>\n*[[Bachelor of Science]] (BSc) in [[Physics]] | [[Mathematics]] | [[Statistics]] | [[Chemistry]] | [[Zoology]] | [[Botany]] | [[Environmental science|Environmental Science]] | Computer Science and Information Technology (CSIT)\n*[[Bachelor of Arts]] (BA) in Mathematics | [[Economics]] | [[Anthropology]] | [[Cultural studies|Culture]] | [[English language|English]] | [[Nepali language|Nepali]] | [[History]] | [[Political science|Political Science]]\n*[[Bachelor of Business Administration]] (BBA)\n*[[Bachelor of Computer Application]] (BCA)\n*Bachelor of [[Social work|Social Work]] (BSW)\n*[[Business studies|Bachelor of Business Studies]] (BBS)\n*[[Master of Arts]] (MA) in Nepali | Economics | English | Anthropology\n*[[Business studies|Master of Business Studies]] (MBS)\n\nBetween 2068 and 2074 BS, Mechi Multiple Campus offered a unique program called Bachelor of Science in Tea Technology and Management (BScTTM), being the only college in the country to offer an undergraduate tea course.<ref name = \"post\"/> A large part of Nepal\u2019s tea industry is based in [[Eastern Development Region, Nepal|eastern Nepal]], particularly in [[Jhapa District|Jhapa]] and [[Ilam District|Ilam]] districts, and the program was offered with the aim of availing the requirement of qualified and skilled human resource in the tea sector.<ref name=\"post\">{{cite web|title=Few students enrol in tea technology course|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2015-10-28/few-students-enrol-in-tea-technology-course.html|website=[[The Kathmandu Post]]|publisher=[[Kantipur Publications]]|accessdate=26 June 2016|date=28 October 2015}}</ref> Despite the enormous potential, the tea management course failed to attract students, with the enrollment dropping drastically from 23 students in the first batch to just 6 in the third batch.<ref name=\"ttm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sajhamanch.com/english/3435.html|title=B. Sc.Tea Technology and Management Problems and Prospects|author1=Prithibi Bikram Rai|date=17 November 2014|website=SajhaManch.com|accessdate=27 July 2016}}</ref> The decrease in the number of students was attributed partly to the ineffective publicity of the academic course and partly to the uncertainties looming over its prospects.<ref name = \"ttm\"/> The program was eventually dropped in 2074 BS.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.blastkhabar.com/news/2018/08/11/90387.html|title=\u092a\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0935\u093f\u0927\u093f\u0915 \u0936\u093f\u0915\u094d\u0937\u093e\u0932\u0947 \u092b\u0947\u0930\u093f\u090f\u0915\u094b \u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940 \u092c\u0939\u0941\u092e\u0941\u0916\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938|last=|first=|date=|website=Blast Khabar|language=ne-NP|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-09|quote=\u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938\u092e\u093e \u092c\u093f\u090f\u0938\u094d\u0938\u0940 \u091f\u093f\u091f\u093f\u090f\u092e(\u091a\u093f\u092f\u093e \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0935\u093f\u0927\u093f) \u092d\u0928\u0947 \u0939\u093e\u0932 \u0935\u093f\u0926\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0930\u094d\u0925\u0940 \u0928\u092d\u090f\u0930 \u090f\u0915 \u0935\u0930\u094d\u0937\u092f\u0924\u093e\u0926\u0947\u0916\u093f \u092a\u0920\u0928\u2013\u092a\u093e\u0920\u0928 \u092c\u0928\u094d\u0926 \u092d\u090f\u0915\u094b \u091b \u0964}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 December 2016, the [[Commission for the Investigation of Abuse of Authority (CIAA)]] raided six colleges in [[Jhapa]], including Mechi Multiple Campus, as per the complaints lodged at the anti-graft body that some of the professors of public colleges were teaching in private colleges alongside. Umanath Oli{{Snd}}the then-chief at Mechi Multiple Campus{{Snd}}was reported to have admitted that some professors had invested in private colleges and took classes there. He claimed that they had been doing so before the provision of requiring approval from the university monitoring commission came into effect.<ref name=\"tkp\">{{cite news|title=CIAA raids 6 colleges|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2014-12-29/ciaa-raids-6-colleges.html|accessdate=28 July 2016|website=[[The Kathmandu Post]]|publisher=[[Kantipur Publications]]|date=30 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nStudents wings affiliated to the [[Nepal Communist Party]], [[Nepali Congress]], and [[Rastriya Prajatantra Party]] are operative in Mechi Multiple Campus. The last Free Students' Union (FSU) election was held in the campus on 1 March 2017.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n\nSome of the eminent graduates of the college include Yubaraj Khatiwada (Finance Minister of Nepal), CP Mainali (former Deputy Prime Minister), RK Mainali (politician),<ref name=\"Purwanchal\">{{cite web|title=\u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940 \u092c\u0939\u0941\u092e\u0941\u0916\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938\u092e\u093e \u0935\u093f\u0926\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0930\u094d\u0925\u0940\u0915\u094b \u091a\u093e\u092a \u0918\u091f\u094d\u092f\u094b|url=http://onlinepurbanchal.com/punews/purbanchal-news/818|website=onlinepurwanchal.com|accessdate=11 August 2016|date=27 May 2011}}</ref> Biswa Prakash Sharma (Nepali Congress leader),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theyouthtimes.com/news-details/229/2018-01-09|title=Nepali Congress appoints Youth leader Biswa Prakash Sharma appointed as Spokesperson|last=|first=|date=|website=The Youth Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref> Rajendra Lingden ([[Rastriya Prajatantra Party]] leader), and Arpan Sharma Kattel (Guinness World Record holder).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saptahik.ekantipur.com/news/2017-01-09/20170109140357.html|title=\u092e\u0947\u092e\u094b\u0930\u0940 \u0915\u093f\u0919|website=saptahik.ekantipur.com|language=Nepali|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref> \n<gallery>\nFile:Yubaraj Khatiwada.jpg|Former governor of [[Nepal Rastra Bank]] Yubaraj Khatiwada\nFile:CP Mainali.jpg|Former Deputy Prime Minister [[Chandra Prakash Mainali|CP Mainali]]\nFile:RK Mainali.jpg|Communist politician [[Radha Krishna Mainali|RK Mainali]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of universities and colleges in Nepal]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist|2}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.mechicampus.edu.np Mechi Multiple Campus]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://mechicampus.edu.np Archived pages of the official website] on the [[Wayback Machine]]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Nepal]]\n[[Category:Education in Nepal]]\n", "text_old": "{{Coord|26.560768|N|88.086594|E|type:edu|display=title}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}  \n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}} \n{{Infobox university\n| name = Mechi Multiple Campus\n| native_name = \u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940 \u092c\u0939\u0941\u092e\u0941\u0916\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938\n| native_name_lang = ne\n| image_name = Mechi Multiple Campus 1.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Western entrance to the campus\n| established = 1964 (2021 BS)\n| type = [[Public]]\n| affiliation = [[Tribhuvan University]]\n| address = [[Bhadrapur, Mechi|Bhadrapur]]-8, [[Jhapa]]\n| city = \n| country = [[Nepal]]\n| sports_nickname = MMC\n| principal = Kamal Prasad Guragain\n| academic_staff = 126\n| administrative_staff = 54\n| students = 1,800\n| campus = [[Rural area]], 27 acres\n| language = [[Nepali language|Nepali]], [[English language|English]]\n| website = http://mechicampus.edu.np\n}}\n\n'''Mechi Multiple Campus''' ({{lang-ne|[[:ne:\u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940 \u092c\u0939\u0941\u092e\u0941\u0916\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938|\u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940 \u092c\u0939\u0941\u092e\u0941\u0916\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938]]}}) is a constituent campus of [[Tribhuvan University]] in [[Bhadrapur, Mechi|Bhadrapur]] municipality of [[Jhapa]] district.<ref name=\"mechi\">{{cite web|title=Homepage of Mechi Multiple Campus|url=http://www.mechicampus.edu.np/|publisher=Mechi Multiple Campus|accessdate=4 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"TU\">{{cite web|title=List of Constituent Campuses|url=http://tribhuvan-university.edu.np/academics/campuses/|website=|publisher=Tribhuvan University|accessdate=26 June 2016}}</ref> Founded in 1964, it is the only constituent campus of Tribhuvan University in the district.<ref name=\"MMC\">{{cite web|last1=Basistha|first1=Chudamani|title=\u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940 \u092c\u0939\u0941\u092e\u0941\u0916\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938 \u0939\u093f\u091c\u094b, \u0906\u091c \u0930 \u092d\u094b\u0932\u093f|url=http://www.sajhamanch.com/profile/3007.html|website=sajhamanch.com|date=1 September 2014|accessdate=26 June 2016}}</ref> As of August 2017, 126 academic and 54 administrative staffs were employed at the college.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.blastkhabar.com/news/2018/08/11/90387.html|title=\u092a\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0935\u093f\u0927\u093f\u0915 \u0936\u093f\u0915\u094d\u0937\u093e\u0932\u0947 \u092b\u0947\u0930\u093f\u090f\u0915\u094b \u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940 \u092c\u0939\u0941\u092e\u0941\u0916\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938|last=|first=|date=|website=Blast Khabar|language=ne-NP|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-09|quote=\u0967 \u0938\u092f \u0968\u096c \u091c\u0928\u093e \u0936\u093f\u0915\u094d\u0937\u0915 \u0930 \u096b\u096a \u091c\u0928\u093e \u0915\u0930\u094d\u092e\u091a\u093e\u0930\u0940 \u0915\u093e\u0930\u094d\u092f\u0930\u0924 \u0930\u0939\u0947\u0915\u094b \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0936\u093e\u0938\u0928 \u0936\u093e\u0916\u093e\u0932\u0947 \u091c\u0928\u093e\u090f\u0915\u094b \u091b \u0964}}</ref> Since June 2016, the college administration has been headed by Kamal Prasad Guragain, who is often referred to as \"Campus Chief.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khabarmanch.com/campus-chief/|title=\u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940 \u092c\u0939\u0941\u092e\u0941\u0916\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938\u0915\u094b \u092a\u094d\u0930\u092e\u0941\u0916\u092e\u093e \u0915\u092e\u0932 \u0917\u0941\u0930\u093e\u0917\u093e\u0908\u0901|date=18 June 2016|website=khabarmanch.com|language=Nepali|accessdate=11 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nTo begin with, the college offered an [[Intermediate of Arts]] (IA) program in [[humanities]], which was soon followed by undergraduate programs. At present, the college runs undergraduate and postgraduate programs. The intermediate programs were fully scrapped in 2010, following Tribhuvan University's decision to phase out Proficiency Certificate Level (PCL) programs from its colleges. This termination of PCL programs brought about a sharp decline in the number of students at the college.<ref name = \"MMC\"/> In its heyday, the college had about 5,000 students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.blastkhabar.com/news/2018/08/11/90387.html|title=\u092a\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0935\u093f\u0927\u093f\u0915 \u0936\u093f\u0915\u094d\u0937\u093e\u0932\u0947 \u092b\u0947\u0930\u093f\u090f\u0915\u094b \u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940 \u092c\u0939\u0941\u092e\u0941\u0916\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938|last=|first=|date=|website=Blast Khabar|language=ne-NP|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-09|quote=\u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938\u092e\u093e \u096b \u0939\u091c\u093e\u0930 \u0935\u093f\u0926\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0930\u094d\u0925\u0940 \u0905\u0927\u094d\u092f\u092f\u0928\u0915\u093e \u0932\u093e\u0917\u093f \u0906\u0907\u0930\u0939\u0947\u0915\u094b \u0905\u0935\u0938\u094d\u0925\u093e\u092e\u093e \u0935\u093f\u0936\u094d\u0935\u0935\u093f\u0926\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0932\u092f\u0932\u0947 \u0928\u093f\u092f\u092e \u092e\u093f\u091a\u0947\u0930 \u090f\u0915 \u0915\u093f\u0932\u094b\u092e\u093f\u091f\u0930\u0915\u094b \u0926\u0942\u0930\u0940\u092e\u093e \u0938\u094d\u0928\u093e\u0924\u0915 \u0924\u0939 \u0905\u0927\u094d\u092f\u092f\u0928\u0915\u094b \u0932\u093e\u0917\u093f \u0905\u0928\u0941\u092e\u0924\u093f \u0926\u093f\u090f\u0915\u093e \u0915\u093e\u0930\u0923 \u0935\u093f\u0926\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0930\u094d\u0925\u0940 \u0938\u0919\u094d\u0916\u094d\u092f\u093e \u0918\u091f\u0947\u0915\u094b \u0909\u0928\u0932\u0947 \u092c\u0924\u093e\u090f \u0964}}</ref> Today the number is around 1,800.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jhapaonline.com/?p=24349|title=\u0917\u0941\u0932\u094d\u091c\u093e\u0930\u200c \u092e\u0947\u200c\u091a\u0940 \u092c\u0939\u0941\u092e\u0941\u0916\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938|last=|first=|date=2019-08-28|website=Jhapa Online|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-09|quote=\u0915\u0941\u0928\u0948\u200c \u092c\u0947\u200c\u0932\u093e \u0932\u0917\u092d\u0917 \u096d \u0938\u092f \u0935\u093f\u0926\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0930\u094d\u0925\u0940 \u092e\u093e\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u0905\u0927\u094d\u092f\u092f\u0928 \u0917\u0928\u0947\u0930\u094d\u200c \u092f\u094b\u200c \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938\u092e\u093e \u0939\u093e\u0932 \u0967,\u096e\u0966\u0966 \u0935\u093f\u0926\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0930\u094d\u0925\u0940 \u0935\u093f\u092d\u093f\u0928\u094d\u0928 \u0938\u0902\u0915\u093e\u092f\u0917\u0924 \u0935\u093f\u0937\u092f\u092e\u093e \u0905\u0927\u094d\u092f\u092f\u0928\u0930\u200c\u0924\u094d \u091b\u0928\u094d\u202f\u0964}}</ref> The college received the Quality Assurance and Accreditation (QAA) certification from the University Grants Commission (UGC) on March 6, 2019.\n\n==History==\n\nWith inauguration by Brigadier General Bhupalman Singh Karki, Mechi Multiple Campus was established on 12 Ashwin 2021 [[Vikram Samvat|BS]] (27 September 1964 CE). With no private building for the next five years, classes in those early years of inception were imparted only in the evening, in the premises of Bhadrapur Red Cross and Bhadrapur High School. The construction of college's physical infrastructure began to gather pace from 2024{{nbsp}}[[Vikram Samvat|BS]] ({{circa}}{{nbsp}}1967{{nbsp}}CE),{{efn|Because [[Vikram Samvat]] leads the [[Gregorian calendar]] by 56.7 years, the CE year can be best approximated by subtracting 56.7 from the BS year and rounding it down to the nearest integral value.}} and it took three years until completion. The college was relocated to its present place in 2027{{nbsp}}[[Vikram Samvat|BS]] ({{circa}}{{nbsp}}1970{{nbsp}}CE).<ref name = \"MMC\"/>\n\nThe college celebrated its golden jubilee in the year 2071{{nbsp}}[[Vikram Samvat|BS]].<ref name=\"mechi\"/> The golden jubilee was commemorated with programmes and extra-curricular activities all year round, including a major three-day cultural event in Ashwin.<ref name=\"majheri\">{{cite web|title=\u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938 \u092d\u0926\u094d\u0930\u092a\u0941\u0930\u0915\u093e\u0947 \u0938\u0942\u091a\u0928\u093e|url=http://www.majheri.com/node/15043|website=majheri.com|accessdate=13 August 2016|language=Nepali|date=22 July 2014}}</ref> Inaugurated by the then-President [[Ram Baran Yadav]], who was the chief guest, the cultural event saw attendance from a host of alumni, donors, politicians, and national dignitaries{{Snd}}including the then-Governor of [[Nepal Rastra Bank]] Yuba Raj Khatiwada, the [[Nepali Congress]] leader Krishna Prasad Sitaula, and [[Communist Party of Nepal (Unified Marxist\u2013Leninist)|CPN\u2013UML]]'s Agni Kharel.<ref name=\"nepaljapan\">{{cite web|title=\u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940 \u092c\u0939\u0941\u092e\u0941\u0916\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938\u0915\u094b \u0938\u094d\u0935\u0930\u094d\u0923 \u092e\u0939\u094b\u0924\u094d\u0938\u0935|url=http://www.nepaljapan.com/%E0%A4%AE%E0%A5%87%E0%A4%9A%E0%A5%80-%E0%A4%AC%E0%A4%B9%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%AE%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%96%E0%A5%80-%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%AF%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%AE%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%AA%E0%A4%B8%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%8B/|website=nepaljapan.com|accessdate=13 August 2016|language=Nepali|date=19 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"nagarikfm\">{{cite web|title=\u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940 \u092c\u0939\u0941\u092e\u0941\u0916\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938\u0915\u094b \u0938\u094d\u0935\u0930\u094d\u0923\u092e\u0939\u094b\u0924\u094d\u0935\u0938 \u0938\u092e\u093e\u0930\u094b\u0939 \u092d\u0935\u094d\u092f\u0924\u093e\u0915\u093e \u0938\u093e\u0925 \u0938\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0928\u094d\u0928|url=http://www.nagarikfm.com.np/news/%E0%A4%AE%E0%A5%87%E0%A4%9A%E0%A5%80-%E0%A4%AC%E0%A4%B9%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%AE%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%96%E0%A5%80-%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%AF%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%AE%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%AA%E0%A4%B8%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%8B/|website=nagarikfm.com.np|accessdate=13 August 2016|language=Nepali|date=20 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160814104218/http://www.nagarikfm.com.np/news/%E0%A4%AE%E0%A5%87%E0%A4%9A%E0%A5%80-%E0%A4%AC%E0%A4%B9%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%AE%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%96%E0%A5%80-%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%AF%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%AE%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%AA%E0%A4%B8%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%8B/|archive-date=14 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\n\nThe campus, which spreads over an area of 16 [[bigha]]s ({{circa}} 27 acres),{{efn|The [[bigha]] is a local unit of land measurement, standardized to 72,000 square feet.|name=|group=}} is in a rural environment, about 1&nbsp;km northeast of [[Bhadrapur Airport]]. The area has a mediocre access to road transportation. The campus yard constitutes a small canteen, a cricket and a football ground, a semi-constructed basketball court, a tea garden, a soil test lab, an administrative building, a FSU building, and two other major buildings{{Spaced en dash}}one for the science faculty and the other for the rest. A second building in the science yard is also under construction.<ref name = \"mechi\"/>\n\n==Academics==\n[[File:Mechi Multiple Campus.jpg|thumb|300 px|Science block of Mechi Multiple Campus (2015)]]\nThe college offers the following undergraduate and postgraduate programs:<ref name = \"MMC\"/>\n*[[Bachelor of Science]] (BSc) in [[Physics]] | [[Mathematics]] | [[Statistics]] | [[Chemistry]] | [[Zoology]] | [[Botany]] | [[Environmental science|Environmental Science]] | Computer Science and Information Technology (CSIT)\n*[[Bachelor of Arts]] (BA) in Mathematics | [[Economics]] | [[Anthropology]] | [[Cultural studies|Culture]] | [[English language|English]] | [[Nepali language|Nepali]] | [[History]] | [[Political science|Political Science]]\n*[[Bachelor of Business Administration]] (BBA)\n*[[Bachelor of Computer Application]] (BCA)\n*Bachelor of [[Social work|Social Work]] (BSW)\n*[[Business studies|Bachelor of Business Studies]] (BBS)\n*[[Master of Arts]] (MA) in Nepali | Economics | English | Anthropology\n*[[Business studies|Master of Business Studies]] (MBS)\n\nBetween 2068 and 2074 BS, Mechi Multiple Campus offered a unique program called Bachelor of Science in Tea Technology and Management (BScTTM), being the only college in the country to offer an undergraduate tea course.<ref name = \"post\"/> A large part of Nepal\u2019s tea industry is based in [[Eastern Development Region, Nepal|eastern Nepal]], particularly in [[Jhapa District|Jhapa]] and [[Ilam District|Ilam]] districts, and the program was offered with the aim of availing the requirement of qualified and skilled human resource in the tea sector.<ref name=\"post\">{{cite web|title=Few students enrol in tea technology course|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2015-10-28/few-students-enrol-in-tea-technology-course.html|website=[[The Kathmandu Post]]|publisher=[[Kantipur Publications]]|accessdate=26 June 2016|date=28 October 2015}}</ref> Despite the enormous potential, the tea management course failed to attract students, with the enrollment dropping drastically from 23 students in the first batch to just 6 in the third batch.<ref name=\"ttm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sajhamanch.com/english/3435.html|title=B. Sc.Tea Technology and Management Problems and Prospects|author1=Prithibi Bikram Rai|date=17 November 2014|website=SajhaManch.com|accessdate=27 July 2016}}</ref> The decrease in the number of students was attributed partly to the ineffective publicity of the academic course and partly to the uncertainties looming over its prospects.<ref name = \"ttm\"/> The program was eventually dropped in 2074 BS.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.blastkhabar.com/news/2018/08/11/90387.html|title=\u092a\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0935\u093f\u0927\u093f\u0915 \u0936\u093f\u0915\u094d\u0937\u093e\u0932\u0947 \u092b\u0947\u0930\u093f\u090f\u0915\u094b \u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940 \u092c\u0939\u0941\u092e\u0941\u0916\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938|last=|first=|date=|website=Blast Khabar|language=ne-NP|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-09|quote=\u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938\u092e\u093e \u092c\u093f\u090f\u0938\u094d\u0938\u0940 \u091f\u093f\u091f\u093f\u090f\u092e(\u091a\u093f\u092f\u093e \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0935\u093f\u0927\u093f) \u092d\u0928\u0947 \u0939\u093e\u0932 \u0935\u093f\u0926\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0930\u094d\u0925\u0940 \u0928\u092d\u090f\u0930 \u090f\u0915 \u0935\u0930\u094d\u0937\u092f\u0924\u093e\u0926\u0947\u0916\u093f \u092a\u0920\u0928\u2013\u092a\u093e\u0920\u0928 \u092c\u0928\u094d\u0926 \u092d\u090f\u0915\u094b \u091b \u0964}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 December 2016, the [[Commission for the Investigation of Abuse of Authority (CIAA)]] raided six colleges in [[Jhapa]], including Mechi Multiple Campus, as per the complaints lodged at the anti-graft body that some of the professors of public colleges were teaching in private colleges alongside. Umanath Oli{{Snd}}the then-chief at Mechi Multiple Campus{{Snd}}was reported to have admitted that some professors had invested in private colleges and took classes there. He claimed that they had been doing so before the provision of requiring approval from the university monitoring commission came into effect.<ref name=\"tkp\">{{cite news|title=CIAA raids 6 colleges|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2014-12-29/ciaa-raids-6-colleges.html|accessdate=28 July 2016|website=[[The Kathmandu Post]]|publisher=[[Kantipur Publications]]|date=30 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nStudents wings affiliated to the [[Nepal Communist Party]], [[Nepali Congress]], and [[Rastriya Prajatantra Party]] are operative in Mechi Multiple Campus. The last Free Students' Union (FSU) election was held in the campus on 1 March 2017.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n\nSome of the eminent graduates of the college include Yubaraj Khatiwada (Finance Minister of Nepal), CP Mainali (former Deputy Prime Minister), RK Mainali (politician),<ref name=\"Purwanchal\">{{cite web|title=\u092e\u0947\u091a\u0940 \u092c\u0939\u0941\u092e\u0941\u0916\u0940 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u093e\u092e\u094d\u092a\u0938\u092e\u093e \u0935\u093f\u0926\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0930\u094d\u0925\u0940\u0915\u094b \u091a\u093e\u092a \u0918\u091f\u094d\u092f\u094b|url=http://onlinepurbanchal.com/punews/purbanchal-news/818|website=onlinepurwanchal.com|accessdate=11 August 2016|date=27 May 2011}}</ref> Biswa Prakash Sharma (Nepali Congress leader),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theyouthtimes.com/news-details/229/2018-01-09|title=Nepali Congress appoints Youth leader Biswa Prakash Sharma appointed as Spokesperson|last=|first=|date=|website=The Youth Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref> Rajendra Lingden ([[Rastriya Prajatantra Party]] leader), and Arpan Sharma Kattel (Guinness World Record holder).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saptahik.ekantipur.com/news/2017-01-09/20170109140357.html|title=\u092e\u0947\u092e\u094b\u0930\u0940 \u0915\u093f\u0919|website=saptahik.ekantipur.com|language=Nepali|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref> \n<gallery>\nFile:Yubaraj Khatiwada.jpg|Former governor of [[Nepal Rastra Bank]] Yubaraj Khatiwada\nFile:CP Mainali.jpg|Former Deputy Prime Minister [[Chandra Prakash Mainali|CP Mainali]]\nFile:RK Mainali.jpg|Communist politician [[Radha Krishna Mainali|RK Mainali]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of universities and colleges in Nepal]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist|2}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.mechicampus.edu.np Mechi Multiple Campus]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://mechicampus.edu.np Archived pages of the official website] on the [[Wayback Machine]]\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Nepal]]\n[[Category:Education in Nepal]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mechi_Multiple_Campus"}
{"title_page": "Mechatronics Polytechnic of Sanata Dharma", "text_new": "{{Infobox school\n| name              =Mechatronics Polytechnic of Sanata Dharma\n| native_name       = \n| image             = \n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| logo              = PMSDIndonesia.png \n| motto = \n| type              = [[Jesuit]], [[Catholic church|Catholic]]\n| status            = \n| gender            = Coeducational\n| denomination   = All faiths \n| affiliation       = \n| affiliations      = \n<!-- Localizaci\u00f3n -->\n| administrator     = \n| assst_admin       = \n|rector            =  \n| director          =  \n| president         = \n| principal         = \n| asst principal    = \n| dean              =\n| headmaster  = \n|  staff           = 23 lecturers \n| teaching_staff    = \n| enrollment        = \n| grades            = \n| tuition           =  \n| established =   {{Start date and age| 2011 }} \n| streetaddress     =\n| city              = \t[[Yogyakarta]], [[Indonesia]]\n| state             = \n| province          = \n| country           = \n| accreditation     = \n| campus            = \n| colors            = \n| athletics         = \n| nickname          = \n| mascot            = \n| yearbook          = \n|publication   =\n| newspaper          = \n| national_ranking  = \n| free_label1       = \n| free_text1        =\n| free_label2        =\n|free_text2          = \n| free_label3       = \n| free_text3        = \n| website           = {{URL|http://www.pmsd.ac.id}}\n| picture           = \n| picture_caption   = \n}}\n\n'''Mechatronics Polytechnic of Sanata Dharma''' (PMSD) grew out of the [[Jesuit]] [[Sanata Dharma University]] in [[Yogyakarta]], [[Indonesia]], and became a separate institution in 2011.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n==Courses==\nMechatronics Polytechnic of Sanata Dharma offers diploma courses in [[Mechatronics]], Medical Instrumentation, and Mechatronics Product Design. Practice is emphasized over theory, with two-thirds of class time spent in actual practice. The aim is to furnish job-ready graduates in both automated and medical applications, in line with increased industrial automation and health needs in Indonesia.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nPMSD is a member of the Indonesian section of the [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers]] (OEEE).<ref>[http://www.ieeer10.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/IndonesiaSection-edited-L.pdf IRRR participation. Accessed 15 December 2016.]</ref>\n\n==References==  \n{{Reflist|2}}\n{{Coord|7|45|19.21|S|110|25|21.52|E|display=title}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Catholic universities and colleges in Indonesia|U]]\n[[Category:Universities in the Special Region of Yogyakarta]]\n[[Category:Universities in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Sleman Regency]]\n[[Category:Jesuit universities and colleges]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox school\n| name              =Mechatronics Polytechnic of Sanata Dharma\n| native_name       = \n| image             = \n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| logo              = PMSDIndonesia.png \n| motto = \n| type              = [[Jesuit]], [[Catholic church|Catholic]]\n| status            = \n| gender            = Coeducational\n| denomination   = All faiths \n| affiliation       = \n| affiliations      = \n<!-- Localizaci\u00f3n -->\n| administrator     = \n| assst_admin       = \n|rector            =  \n| director          =  \n| president         = \n| principal         = \n| asst principal    = \n| dean              =\n| headmaster  = \n|  staff           = 23 lecturers \n| teaching_staff    = \n| enrollment        = \n| grades            = \n| tuition           =  \n| established =   {{Start date and age| 2011 }} \n| streetaddress     =\n| city              = \t[[Yogyakarta]], [[Indonesia]]\n| state             = \n| province          = \n| country           = \n| accreditation     = \n| campus            = \n| colors            = \n| athletics         = \n| nickname          = \n| mascot            = \n| yearbook          = \n|publication   =\n| newspaper          = \n| national_ranking  = \n| free_label1       = \n| free_text1        =\n| free_label2        =\n|free_text2          = \n| free_label3       = \n| free_text3        = \n| website           = {{URL|http://www.pmsd.ac.id}}\n| picture           = \n| picture_caption   = \n}}\n\n'''Mechatronics Polytechnic of Sanata Dharma''' (PMSD) grew out of the [[Jesuit]] [[Sanata Dharma University]] in [[Yogyakarta]], [[Indonesia]], and became a separate institution in 2011.{{fact|date=January 2019}}\n\n==Courses==\nMechatronics Polytechnic of Sanata Dharma offers diploma courses in [[Mechatronics]], Medical Instrumentation, and Mechatronics Product Design. Practice is emphasized over theory, with two-thirds of class time spent in actual practice. The aim is to furnish job-ready graduates in both automated and medical applications, in line with increased industrial automation and health needs in Indonesia.{{fact|date=January 2019}}\n\nPMSD is a member of the Indonesian section of the [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers]] (OEEE).<ref>[http://www.ieeer10.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/IndonesiaSection-edited-L.pdf IRRR participation. Accessed 15 December 2016.]</ref>\n\n==References==  \n{{Reflist|2}}\n{{Coord|7|45|19.21|S|110|25|21.52|E|display=title}}\n[[Category:Catholic universities and colleges in Indonesia|U]]\n[[Category:Universities in the Special Region of Yogyakarta]]\n[[Category:Universities in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Sleman Regency]]\n[[Category:Jesuit universities and colleges]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mechatronics_Polytechnic_of_Sanata_Dharma"}
{"title_page": "McPherson University", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = McPherson University\n| native_name = \n| image_name = The_McPherson_University_logo.png\n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| motto = To build a People of Excellence and Integrity for Service\n| established = 2012\n| type = Private\n| chancellor = Dr.[[Christopher Kolade]]\n| vice_chancellor = Prof. [[Adeniyi Agunbiade]]\n| faculty = \n| staff = \n| students = Over 500\n| city = \n| state = [[Ogun State]]\n| country = [[Nigeria]]\n| campus = 302.210 acres\n| former_names = LIFE University\n| nickname = McPherson Champions\n| free_label = Newspaper\n| free = McU Echo\n| website = {{Official website|https://www.mcu.edu.ng/home/}}\n}}\n'''McPherson University''' (McU) is a private Christian university in [[Abeokuta]] , Seriki-Sotayo, Ogun State.  Nigeria. It was founded by the  [[Foursquare Gospel Church in Nigeria]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.mcu-edu.ng/pages/universities.asp?ty=3&order=inst_name&page=2| title=National Universities Commission| publisher=National Universities Commission,Nigeria| accessdate=5 July 2013}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://pulse.ng/student/know-your-university-nigeria-s-59-private-universities-locations-vice-chancellors-names-websites-dates-of-establishment-id3687732.html | title=Nigeria\u2019s 59 private universities \u2026locations, Vice Chancellors names, websites, dates of establishment | publisher=pulse.ng | work=Kukogho Iruesiri Samson | date=22 April 2015 | accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Campus==\nThe colleges are located on the east side of the university.\n\nThe university hosts three instructional buildings, a health centre, garden, library and an administration building. The multipurpose hall houses the dining hall and the chapel. Outdoor field sports are played at McPherson Sport Centre. In the summer of 2012, the sport centre was renovated to contain a basketball court, volleyball court and lawn tennis court.\n\n==Courses==\nAs a licensed Institution, McU runs degree programs that award Bachelor of Science and of Arts from three Colleges. The Institution runs pre-degree programs in selected courses.\n\n=== College Of Natural and Applied Sciences ===\nCourses offered at the College of Natural and Applied Sciences (COLNAS) are:\n\n* Microbiology\n* Biochemistry\n* Computer Science\n* Biotechnology\n* Chemistry\n* Mathematics\n* Physics\n* Statistics\n\n=== College of Social and Management Sciences ===\nCourses offered at the College of Social and Management Sciences (COSMAS) are:\n\n* Accounting\n* Banking and Finance\n* Business Administration\n* Economics\n* Marketing\n* International Relations\n* Mass Communications\n\n=== College of Humanities ===\nCourses offered at the College of Humanities (COLHUM) are:\n\n* History and International Studies\n* Religious Studies\n* English Language\n\n== Library ==\n\nThe library is situated besides the administrative office and serves the whole University community. The library houses the college archives, academic support services and career services. It offers computers for student use, with software including internet access and word processing.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.mcu.edu.ng/}}\n{{Universities in Nigeria}}\n{{coord missing|Nigeria}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Ondo State]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2012]]\n[[Category:2012 establishments in Nigeria]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox University\n| name = McPherson University\n| native_name = \n| image_name = The_McPherson_University_logo.png\n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| motto = To build a People of Excellence and Integrity for Service\n| established = 2012\n| type = Private\n| chancellor = Dr.[[Christopher Kolade]]\n| vice_chancellor = Prof. [[Adeniyi Agunbiade]]\n| faculty = \n| staff = \n| students = Over 500\n| city = \n| state = [[Ogun State]]\n| country = [[Nigeria]]\n| campus = 302.210 acres\n| former_names = LIFE University\n| nickname = McPherson Champions\n| free_label = Newspaper\n| free = McU Echo\n| website = {{Official website|https://www.mcu.edu.ng/home/}}\n}}\n'''McPherson University''' (McU) is a private Christian university in [[Abeokuta]] , Seriki-Sotayo, Ogun State.  Nigeria. It was founded by the  [[Foursquare Gospel Church in Nigeria]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.mcu-edu.ng/pages/universities.asp?ty=3&order=inst_name&page=2| title=National Universities Commission| publisher=National Universities Commission,Nigeria| accessdate=5 July 2013}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://pulse.ng/student/know-your-university-nigeria-s-59-private-universities-locations-vice-chancellors-names-websites-dates-of-establishment-id3687732.html | title=Nigeria\u2019s 59 private universities \u2026locations, Vice Chancellors names, websites, dates of establishment | publisher=pulse.ng | work=Kukogho Iruesiri Samson | date=22 April 2015 | accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Campus==\nThe colleges are located on the east side of the university.\n\nThe university hosts three instructional buildings, a health centre, garden, library and an administration building. The multipurpose hall houses the dining hall and the chapel. Outdoor field sports are played at McPherson Sport Centre. In the summer of 2012, the sport centre was renovated to contain a basketball court, volleyball court and lawn tennis court.\n\n==Courses==\nAs a licensed Institution, McU runs degree programs that award Bachelor of Science and of Arts from three Colleges. The Institution runs pre-degree programs in selected courses.\n\n=== College Of Natural and Applied Sciences ===\nCourses offered at the College of Natural and Applied Sciences (COLNAS) are:\n\n* Microbiology\n* Biochemistry\n* Computer Science\n* Biotechnology\n* Chemistry\n* Mathematics\n* Physics\n* Statistics\n\n=== College of Social and Management Sciences ===\nCourses offered at the College of Social and Management Sciences (COSMAS) are:\n\n* Accounting\n* Banking and Finance\n* Business Administration\n* Economics\n* Marketing\n* International Relations\n* Mass Communications\n\n=== College of Humanities ===\nCourses offered at the College of Humanities (COLHUM) are:\n\n* History and International Studies\n* Religious Studies\n* English Language\n\n== Library ==\n\nThe library is situated besides the administrative office and serves the whole University community. The library houses the college archives, academic support services and career services. It offers computers for student use, with software including internet access and word processing.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.mcu.edu.ng/}}\n{{Universities in Nigeria}}\n{{coord missing|Nigeria}}\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Ondo State]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2012]]\n[[Category:2012 establishments in Nigeria]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/McPherson_University"}
{"title_page": "McGhee Center for Eastern Mediterranean Studies", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2017}}\n{{Advert|date=December 2017}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox organization\n|name           = McGhee Center for Eastern Mediterranean Studies\n|bgcolor        = \n|fgcolor        = \n|image          = McGhee Center logo.jpg\n|image_border   = \n|size           = 124\n|alt            = \n|caption        = \n|map            = \n|msize          = \n|malt           = \n|mcaption       = \n|abbreviation   = \n|motto          = \n|formation      = 1989\n|coords         = {{coord|36|32|1.4|N|31|59|45|E|region:TR-07_type:edu|display=title,inline}}\n|type           = Academic center\n|purpose        = \n|headquarters   = \n|location       = [[Alanya]], [[Turkey]]\n|region_served  = \n|membership     = \n|language       = \n|leader_title   = Director\n|leader_name    = Dr. Kay Ebel\n|main_organ     = \n|parent_organization = [[Georgetown University]]\n|affiliations   = [[Ko\u00e7 University]]\n|num_staff      = \n|budget         = \n|website        = [http://mcgheecenter.georgetown.edu/ mcgheecenter.georgetown.edu]\n|remarks        = \n}}\nThe '''McGhee Center for Eastern Mediterranean Studies''' is an overseas academic center operated by [[Georgetown University]] in [[Alanya|Alanya, Turkey]].  The McGhee Center was founded in 1989 after [[George C. McGhee|Ambassador George Crews McGhee]], former [[United States Ambassador to Turkey]] and [[United States Ambassador to Germany|West Germany]], donated his Mediterranean villa to Georgetown University to create a center for the study of the history and culture of Turkey and the Eastern Mediterranean.  The McGhee Center is academically affiliated in Turkey with [[Ko\u00e7 University]] and offers three types of programming: semester abroad, the Summer Institute in Intensive Turkish Language, and study tours and short programs.\n\n==The McGhee Villa and Student Residence==\n[[File:McGhee Center from sea.jpg|thumb|The Villa was built in the 1830s.]]\nThe principle facility of the McGhee Center is the 'McGhee Villa', an Ottoman-era mansion located in the historic district of Alanya, within the old walled city overlooking the harbor.  The villa was built in the early nineteenth century by a local Orthodox Christian merchant who specialized in the export of timber to Egypt.  After [[World War I]] and the collapse of the [[Ottoman Empire]], Alanya\u2019s trade routes were severed and its Christian community departed for Greece.  The villa, like many of Alanya\u2019s grand old Ottoman homes, fell into disrepair and was gradually abandoned as more and more families came to prefer the comfort and convenience of modern apartment buildings.  The villa was noticed by George McGhee and his wife Cecilia on a visit to Alanya during his tenure as U.S. Ambassador to Turkey in the 1950s.  McGhee purchased the property in 1968 and renovated it for his family\u2019s use.  In 1989 he donated the villa to Georgetown University with the intention that it should be used as a center of learning and scholarship.<ref>{{cite book |last=McGhee|first=George|author2=Cecilia McGhee|title=Life in Alanya|year=1992|publisher=Chalidze Publications|location=Benson, Vermont|isbn=1-56541-217-6}}</ref>\n\nStudents and guests at the McGhee Center attend classes, meetings, special events, and take meals at the villa.  The villa also houses a library, study areas, kitchen, faculty and staff offices, and space for visiting lecturers.  The property includes a terraced garden that rises behind the villa, with a gazebo that has views of the sea and the city.  The gardens are planted with tangerine, olive, lemon, pomegranate, bougainvillea, cypress, oleander, loquat, oregano, and cactus.<ref name=bg>{{cite news |url= http://explore.georgetown.edu/documents/?DocumentID=13700 |title= Living History |work= Blue & Gray |date= Spring 2006 |accessdate= 2007-11-08 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060904052431/http://explore.georgetown.edu/documents/?DocumentID=13700 |archivedate= 2006-09-04 }}</ref>\n\nStudents at the McGhee Center are lodged in a student residence, an apartment building located halfway between the villa and downtown Alanya.<ref>Office of International Programs, Georgetown University</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081207172428/http://mcgheecenter.georgetown.edu/ Official site]\n\n{{Georgetown University}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mcghee Center For Eastern Mediterranean Studies}}\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Georgetown University programs]]\n[[Category:Georgetown University buildings]]\n[[Category:Alanya]]\n[[Category:Eastern Mediterranean]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures of the Ottoman Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=December 2017}}\n{{Advert|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox organization\n|name           = McGhee Center for Eastern Mediterranean Studies\n|bgcolor        = \n|fgcolor        = \n|image          = McGhee Center logo.jpg\n|image_border   = \n|size           = 124\n|alt            = \n|caption        = \n|map            = \n|msize          = \n|malt           = \n|mcaption       = \n|abbreviation   = \n|motto          = \n|formation      = 1989\n|coords         = {{coord|36|32|1.4|N|31|59|45|E|region:TR-07_type:edu|display=title,inline}}\n|type           = Academic center\n|purpose        = \n|headquarters   = \n|location       = [[Alanya]], [[Turkey]]\n|region_served  = \n|membership     = \n|language       = \n|leader_title   = Director\n|leader_name    = Dr. Kay Ebel\n|main_organ     = \n|parent_organization = [[Georgetown University]]\n|affiliations   = [[Ko\u00e7 University]]\n|num_staff      = \n|budget         = \n|website        = [http://mcgheecenter.georgetown.edu/ mcgheecenter.georgetown.edu]\n|remarks        = \n}}\nThe '''McGhee Center for Eastern Mediterranean Studies''' is an overseas academic center operated by [[Georgetown University]] in [[Alanya|Alanya, Turkey]].  The McGhee Center was founded in 1989 after [[George C. McGhee|Ambassador George Crews McGhee]], former [[United States Ambassador to Turkey]] and [[United States Ambassador to Germany|West Germany]], donated his Mediterranean villa to Georgetown University to create a center for the study of the history and culture of Turkey and the Eastern Mediterranean.  The McGhee Center is academically affiliated in Turkey with [[Ko\u00e7 University]] and offers three types of programming: semester abroad, the Summer Institute in Intensive Turkish Language, and study tours and short programs.\n\n==The McGhee Villa and Student Residence==\n[[File:McGhee Center from sea.jpg|thumb|The Villa was built in the 1830s.]]\nThe principle facility of the McGhee Center is the 'McGhee Villa', an Ottoman-era mansion located in the historic district of Alanya, within the old walled city overlooking the harbor.  The villa was built in the early nineteenth century by a local Orthodox Christian merchant who specialized in the export of timber to Egypt.  After [[World War I]] and the collapse of the [[Ottoman Empire]], Alanya\u2019s trade routes were severed and its Christian community departed for Greece.  The villa, like many of Alanya\u2019s grand old Ottoman homes, fell into disrepair and was gradually abandoned as more and more families came to prefer the comfort and convenience of modern apartment buildings.  The villa was noticed by George McGhee and his wife Cecilia on a visit to Alanya during his tenure as U.S. Ambassador to Turkey in the 1950s.  McGhee purchased the property in 1968 and renovated it for his family\u2019s use.  In 1989 he donated the villa to Georgetown University with the intention that it should be used as a center of learning and scholarship.<ref>{{cite book |last=McGhee|first=George|author2=Cecilia McGhee|title=Life in Alanya|year=1992|publisher=Chalidze Publications|location=Benson, Vermont|isbn=1-56541-217-6}}</ref>\n\nStudents and guests at the McGhee Center attend classes, meetings, special events, and take meals at the villa.  The villa also houses a library, study areas, kitchen, faculty and staff offices, and space for visiting lecturers.  The property includes a terraced garden that rises behind the villa, with a gazebo that has views of the sea and the city.  The gardens are planted with tangerine, olive, lemon, pomegranate, bougainvillea, cypress, oleander, loquat, oregano, and cactus.<ref name=bg>{{cite news |url= http://explore.georgetown.edu/documents/?DocumentID=13700 |title= Living History |work= Blue & Gray |date= Spring 2006 |accessdate= 2007-11-08 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060904052431/http://explore.georgetown.edu/documents/?DocumentID=13700 |archivedate= 2006-09-04 }}</ref>\n\nStudents at the McGhee Center are lodged in a student residence, an apartment building located halfway between the villa and downtown Alanya.<ref>Office of International Programs, Georgetown University</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081207172428/http://mcgheecenter.georgetown.edu/ Official site]\n\n{{Georgetown University}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mcghee Center For Eastern Mediterranean Studies}}\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Georgetown University programs]]\n[[Category:Georgetown University buildings]]\n[[Category:Alanya]]\n[[Category:Eastern Mediterranean]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures of the Ottoman Empire]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/McGhee_Center_for_Eastern_Mediterranean_Studies"}
{"title_page": "My Maria", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = My Maria\n| cover      = BW Stevenson - My Maria promo.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[B. W. Stevenson]]\n| album      = My Maria\n| B-side     = August Evening Lady\n| released   = August 1973\n| format     = [[7\"]] 45 RPM\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country rock]]\n| length     = 2:25\n| label      = [[RCA Records]]\n| writer     = B. W. Stevenson<br />[[Daniel Moore (musician)|Daniel Moore]]\n| producer   = [[David Kershenbaum]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\"'''My Maria'''\" is a song co-written by [[B. W. Stevenson]] and [[Daniel Moore (musician)|Daniel Moore]]. Stevenson released \"My Maria\" as a single in August 1973, and the song became a Top 10 hit, peaking at number 9 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|US pop chart]]. It remained in the [[Top 40]] for twelve weeks. In addition, \"My Maria\" spent one week at number 1 on the [[Hot Adult Contemporary Tracks|US adult contemporary chart]].<ref>{{cite book |title= Top Adult Contemporary: 1961-2001|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2002 |publisher=Record Research |page=232}}</ref>  The guitar portion of the track was played by [[Larry Carlton]].<ref>[[Joel Whitburn|Whitburn, Joel]] (1996). ''The Billboard Book of Top 40 Hits'', 6th Edition (Billboard Publications)</ref>  A cover version by [[Brooks & Dunn]] reached number 1 on the [[Hot Country Songs|US country music chart]] and won the [[39th Annual Grammy Awards|1997 Grammy]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Country Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal|Country Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal]].\n\n==Chart history==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1973)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100\n|align=\"center\"|9\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' Easy Listening\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|Canada ''RPM'' Top Singles\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|-\n|Canada ''RPM'' Adult Contemporary\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|}\n\n{{-}}\n\n==Brooks & Dunn version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = My Maria\n| cover      = Brooks & Dunn - My Maria promo.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Brooks & Dunn]]\n| album      = [[Borderline (Brooks & Dunn album)|Borderline]]\n| B-side     = [[Mama Don't Get Dressed Up for Nothing]]\n| released   = March 24, 1996<ref>[http://music.aol.com/album/my-maria/382043 AOL Music profile] for \"My Maria\"</ref>\n| format     = [[CD single]], [[Cassette Single]]\n| recorded   = 1995\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = 3:30\n| label      = [[Arista Records|Arista]] 12993\n| writer     = [[B. W. Stevenson]]<br />Daniel Moore\n| producer   = [[Kix Brooks]]<br />[[Don Cook]]<br />[[Ronnie Dunn]]\n| prev_title = [[Whiskey Under the Bridge]]\n| prev_year  = 1995\n| next_title = [[I Am That Man]]\n| next_year  = 1996\n}}\nWhen [[country music]] duo [[Brooks & Dunn]] released a [[cover version]] of \"My Maria\" in 1996, the song reached number 1 on the [[Hot Country Songs|US country chart]]. Their version of the song appears on their album ''[[Borderline (Brooks & Dunn album)|Borderline]]'', released in 1996 on [[Arista Records]]. In addition, their version was the number one country song of 1996 according to Billboard, and won the duo its second Grammy Award for Best Country Performance by a Vocal Group or Duo.<ref name=\"whitburn\">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944 to 2008|publisher=Record Research, Inc|year=2008|page=63|isbn=0-89820-177-2}}</ref> The song's [[b-side]], \"Mama Don't Get Dressed Up for Nothing,\" would later be released as the album's third single.\n\nIn addition, this song was performed as their last performance as a duo at the 2010 [[Academy of Country Music|ACM Awards]] on April 18, 2010, as well at the 50th anniversary of the ACM Awards on April 19, 2015.\n\n===Chart history===\n\"My Maria\" debuted at number 30 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot Country Songs chart for the week of April 6, 1996.\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1996)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadacountry|1|chartid=2973|publishdate=May 20, 1996|accessdate=July 20, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|79|artist=Brooks & Dunn}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcountrysongs|1|artist=Brooks & Dunn}}\n|}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (1996)\n!scope=\"col\"|Position\n|-\n| Canada Country Tracks (''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.9734&type=1&interval=24|title=RPM Top 100 Country Tracks of 1996|work=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|date=December 16, 1996|accessdate=July 20, 2013}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | 12\n|-\n| US [[Hot Country Songs|Country Songs]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/1996/hot-country-songs| title=Best of 1996: Country Songs | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | date=1996| accessdate=July 20, 2013}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | 1\n|}\n\n==Gear Daddies version==\n[[Gear Daddies]] released a version of the song on their 1992 album ''[[Can't Have Nothin' Nice]]''.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List_of_one-hit_wonders_in_the_United_States#1970s|List of 1970s one-hit wonders in the United States]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List_of_one-hit_wonders_in_the_United_States#1970s|List of 1970s one-hit wonders in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|bw-stevenson|my-maria}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Brooks & Dunn singles}}\n{{Billboard Year-End Hot Country Singles number one single of the year}}\n\n[[Category:1973 singles]]\n[[Category:1996 singles]]\n[[Category:1973 songs]]\n[[Category:B. W. Stevenson songs]]\n[[Category: